In late September 1926, Jawish signed to play professional football with the Pottsville Maroons of the National Football League (NFL), prior to their second game of the season, against the Media Athletic Association.[12] He was signed as a tackle but also saw playing time as a guard during the season.[1][12] Jawish became the first and only NFL player from Emerson Preparatory, as well as the third NFL player who had attended George Washington.[13][14] He finished the season having appeared in nine games, four as a starter, as the team compiled a record of 10–2–2.[15] He did not continue playing professional football after the 1926 season.[1] Jawish stood at 5 feet 8 inches (1.73 m) and weighed 210 pounds (95 kg) in the NFL.[1] As of 2025, he remains the only NFL player to have been born in Syria.[16][clarification needed]
After his football career, Jawish worked as a real estate broker, building apartments in the Washington, D.C.-area.[2] Shortly before his death, he worked on a $1.5 million sale of an apartment to Statler Hotel Corp.[17] Jawish was a freemason and a member of the Dawson Masonic Lodge.[2] He was married to Marjorie Jawish and had two sons with her, including Gary, a boxer.[2][18] He often played handball.[2] On March 14, 1941, he collapsed and died while playing handball at the YMCA in Washington.[2] He was 41 at the time of his death.[2]